
📘 How to Install a Custom CSS File in Safari (macOS) Safari does not support user stylesheets directly anymore, but it does include a built‑in Userscripts system that allows you to load your own CSS without installing any extensions or using admin permissions. Follow these steps to enable a custom CSS file globally in Safari.

Create the Safari Userscripts Folder Safari looks for user‑provided scripts in this directory: Code ~/Library/Application Scripts/com.apple.Safari/ If it doesn’t exist, create it: Code mkdir -p ~/Library/Application\ Scripts/com.apple.Safari
Add Your CSS File Place your custom CSS file inside that folder. For example: Code ~/Library/Application Scripts/com.apple.Safari/theme.css You can rename the file to anything you like.
Create a Userscript to Inject the CSS Safari requires a small JavaScript file to load your CSS into every webpage. Create a file in the same folder, for example: Code ~/Library/Application Scripts/com.apple.Safari/theme.js Add the following code: js // Inject theme.css into every page var link = document.createElement("link"); link.rel = "stylesheet"; link.href = safari.extension.baseURI + "theme.css"; document.documentElement.appendChild(link); Save the file.
Enable Userscripts in Safari Open Safari Go to Safari → Settings Open the Extensions tab Find Userscripts in the sidebar Enable it Allow it to run on all websites Turn on your script (e.g., theme.js) Safari will now automatically inject your CSS into every webpage you visit. ✔️ Done Your custom CSS theme is now active system‑wide in Safari. You can edit the CSS file at any time — just refresh the page to see changes.
